Implemented Vercel Speed Insights for Next.js

SUMMARY:
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the Next.js 14.2.4 project using the App Router pattern.

CHANGES MADE:

1. Installed @vercel/speed-insights package:
   - Used npm (the project's package manager) to install @vercel/speed-insights
   - Package successfully added to dependencies in package.json

2. Modified app/layout.tsx:
   - Added import statement: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/next"`
   - Added <SpeedInsights /> component inside the <body> tag
   - Placed it after {children}, <Navbar />, and <CustomCursor /> components
   - Used the correct Next.js 13.5+ App Router import path

3. Updated lock files:
   - package-lock.json was automatically updated with the new dependency and its 441 sub-dependencies

VERIFICATION:
- ✅ Build completed successfully with `npm run build`
- ✅ Linter ran without introducing any new errors
- ✅ All static pages generated correctly (12/12)
- ✅ No breaking changes introduced to existing functionality

IMPLEMENTATION NOTES:
- The project uses Next.js 14.2.4 with App Router, so we used the '@vercel/speed-insights/next' import
- The SpeedInsights component was added as the last child in the <body> tag to ensure it doesn't interfere with existing components
- No additional configuration was needed as the component works automatically when deployed on Vercel
- The existing warnings in canvas-reveal-effect.tsx and hover-border-gradient.tsx are pre-existing and not related to this change

FILES MODIFIED:
- app/layout.tsx - Added SpeedInsights import and component
- package.json - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
- package-lock.json - Updated with new dependency tree
